SIMPLE: peevish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peevish
<hw>Pee"vish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pevische</ets>; of uncertain origin, perh. from a word imitative of
the noise made by fretful children + <ets>-ish</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Habitually fretful; easily vexed or fretted; hard to please; apt to
complain; querulous; petulant.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Her <xex>peevish</xex>
babe.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She is <qex>peevish</qex>, sullen, froward.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expressing fretfulness and discontent, or
unjustifiable dissatisfaction; <as>as, a <ex>peevish</ex>
answer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Silly; childish; trifling.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To send such <qex>peevish</qex> tokens to a king.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Querulous; petulant; cross; ill-tempered; testy;
captious; discontented. See <er>Fretful</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peevishly</ent>⟦br⟧
